            <scriptDesc>
              <summary>
                <p>This manuscript represents a script style close to <hi rend="italic">kūfī </hi>type C.Ia influenced by the early <hi rend="italic">kūfī </hi>script style B.Iand <hi rend="italic">ḥiǧāzī IV</hi>. The letter<hi rend="italic"> ʾalif</hi> resembles the C.Ia group. Within a word, the letters <hi rend="italic">ǧīm/ḥāʾ/ḫāʾ</hi> cross the base line diagonally as those of B.I group, unlike those of C.Ia, where the letter rests on the base line. The tail of the letter in the final position is horizontal as those of C.Ia. The letter <hi rend="italic">ʿayn</hi> in the initial position is close to C.Ia but shows an interesting form of the upper hook: the hook has a rounded shape that looks like a dot, that cannot be seen in any other script groups. Within a word the letter resembles the B.Ib group, the right hand antenna being vertical. The final form of the letter is identical to those seen in the D.IV group, but is also close to the B.I/B.II group. The letter <hi rend="italic">qāf</hi> isolated or in the final position is similar to those of C.Ia group. The initial and medial forms of the letter <hi rend="italic">hāʾ</hi>, alongside with the letter <hi rend="italic">nūn </hi>in the final or isolated position and the letter <hi rend="italic">mīm</hi> at the end of a word show a similar form seen in the <hi rend="italic">ḥiǧāzī IV</hi> manuscript <ref target="https://corpuscoranicum.de/de/verse-navigator/sura/1/verse/1/manuscripts/53">Saray 50385</ref> from Istanbul, the script of which also shows similarities to the C.Ia group. As for the ligature <hi rend="italic">lām-ʾalif</hi>, the form is similar to the C.Ia group.</p>
                <p>F. Déroche relates the script of the sister fragment <ref target="https://corpuscoranicum.de/en/verse-navigator/sura/3/verse/66/manuscripts/33">BnF Arabe 332</ref>  to the C.Ia group (<ref target="https://www.zotero.org/groups/corpuscoranicum_pub/items/itemKey/KCAZQ5NS" sameAs="KCAZQ5NS" type="zotero">See Déroche 1983: p. 77</ref>). The script of the second sister fragment, <ref target="https://corpuscoranicum.de/en/verse-navigator/sura/64/verse/14/manuscripts/893">KFQ 49</ref> from the Khalili Collections in London is categorized by Déroche as 'unclassified', although he links the manuscript with Arabe 332 (<ref target="https://www.zotero.org/groups/corpuscoranicum_pub/items/itemKey/QJQEKNSJ" sameAs="QJQEKNSJ" type="zotero">See Déroche 1992: p. 129</ref>).   </p>
                <p>The manuscript shows occasional diacritical marking, but no signs of vocalisation. </p>
              </summary>
